WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
This is Jacob's Research Journal. Today's deep dive: The Loop

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Is Closing — Recursive Self-Improvement Has Left the Lab. Ninety

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
percent of Claude's code is written by Claude. Not by

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
the engineers at Anthropic who designed the model, but by

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
a previous version of the model itself — iterating on

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
its own codebase, proposing changes, testing them, shipping them. An

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Anthropic spokesperson told Fortune that company-wide, the figure for A-I-generated

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
code is between seventy and ninety percent. At some leading

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
engineers' desks at both Anthropic and OpenAI, it's reportedly one

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
hundred percent. That number alone should stop you. It means

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
the tools that are reshaping entire industries are increasingly built

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
not by human hands but by earlier versions of themselves.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
The concept has a name that has bounced around A-I

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
safety circles for decades — recursive self-improvement, or R-S-I —

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
and as of spring twenty twenty-six, it has migrated from

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
philosophical thought experiment to operational reality at every major A-I

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
laboratory on earth. Now let's talk about where this idea

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
came from — and how fast it became real. The

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
idea is older than most people realize. In nineteen sixty-five,

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
the British mathematician I. J. Good described what he called

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
an intelligence explosion — an ultra-intelligent machine that could design

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
even better machines, creating a feedback loop where, quote, "the

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
intelligence of man would be left far behind." For sixty

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
years this remained a theoretical curiosity, the kind of thing

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
discussed at philosophy conferences and in science fiction novels. It

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
is not theoretical anymore. At the World Economic Forum in

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Davos this January, the C-E-Os of the two companies arguably

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
closest to the frontier — Dario Amodei of Anthropic and

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Demis Hassabis of Google DeepMind — both spoke publicly about

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
pursuing self-improvement research. Hassabis was strikingly direct. He said: "It

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
remains to be seen — can that self-improvement loop that

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
we're all working on — actually close, without a human

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
in the loop." The phrasing is worth sitting with. Not

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
"whether we should work on this" but "whether the loop

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
we're building can close." The decision to pursue R-S-I, at

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
DeepMind at least, appears to have already been made. Anthropic's

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
position is, if anything, more aggressive. Amodei predicted at Davos

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
that the industry may be six to twelve months away

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
from A-I handling most or all of software engineering from

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
start to finish. His company's own chief scientist, Jared Kaplan,

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
has been more explicit about what comes after that. He

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
told Control A-I that humans will face an "extremely high-risk

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
decision" between twenty twenty-seven and twenty thirty — whether to

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
allow A-I systems to independently train and develop the next

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
generation of A-I. Kaplan called this "the ultimate risk." Note

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
the tension: Anthropic's chief scientist publicly calls the thing his

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
company is building "the ultimate risk," while the company continues

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
building it. Now let's look at the lab race —

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
because every major frontier lab has a concrete timeline for

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
automating its own research. The specificity is new, and striking.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
OpenAI has been the most explicit. C-E-O Sam Altman announced

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
internal goals of having an "automated A-I research intern" by

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
September twenty twenty-six, running on hundreds of thousands of G-P-Us,

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
and "a true automated A-I researcher" by March twenty twenty-eight.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Altman added a caveat — "We may totally fail at

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
this goal" — but followed it with a justification that

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
reveals how seriously the company takes it: "given the extraordinary

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
potential impacts we think it is in the public interest

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
to be transparent about this." Chief scientist Jakub Pachocki described

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
this target as "a system capable of autonomously delivering on

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
larger research projects." Anthropic is tracking toward what it calls

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
"fully automated A-I research" by twenty twenty-seven. Dario Amodei has

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
cited something like four hundred percent efficiency improvements per year

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
from optimization work — coding, architecture tweaks, infrastructure engineering —

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
creating a compound effect where identical compute yields dramatically better

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
results each cycle. Dean Ball, a senior fellow at the

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Foundation for American Innovation, calls this a "compute multiplier." An

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
anonymous Anthropic employee captured the aspiration with uncomfortable clarity: "We

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
want Claude n to build Claude n-plus-one, so we can

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
go home and knit sweaters." Google DeepMind has taken a

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
more measured public posture while publishing the most concrete technical

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
results. AlphaEvolve, unveiled in May twenty twenty-five, is an evolutionary

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
coding agent that uses Gemini to generate, mutate, and select

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
algorithmic improvements in a self-reinforcing loop. The results are not

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
speculative: AlphaEvolve has improved Flash Attention operations by thirty-two percent,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
achieved a twenty-three percent speedup in kernel tiling for A-I

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
training, and continuously recovers zero point seven percent of Google's

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
entire worldwide compute resources. That last number sounds small until

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
you consider Google's scale. Zero point seven percent of their

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
compute is a staggering amount of freed capacity, running continuously,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
discovered by an A-I optimizing A-I infrastructure. Meta published a

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
December twenty twenty-five preprint explicitly aimed at using self-improvement techniques

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
to build superintelligence. The paper, notably, contained no mention of

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
safety or ethics. Meanwhile, Meta's former chief A-I scientist Yann

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
LeCun left the company in late twenty twenty-five to found

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
A-M-I Labs, raising one point zero three billion dollars at

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
a three and a half billion dollar valuation — the

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
largest seed-stage investment in European history. LeCun's departure is the

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
highest-profile dissent from the R-S-I consensus: he's betting that the

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
self-improvement loop, as currently conceived, runs into fundamental limits. And

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
the loop isn't limited to software. Ricursive Intelligence, founded by

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
former DeepMind researchers, raised three hundred million dollars at a

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
four billion dollar valuation less than two months after emerging

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
from stealth. Their thesis: A-I designs the silicon that powers

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
the next generation of A-I. The loop extends all the

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
way down to the hardware. Now, let's talk about what

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
I'm calling the Karpathy Moment. If the lab race is

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
R-S-I behind closed doors, Andrej Karpathy blew the doors open.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
In March twenty twenty-six, the former Tesla A-I director and

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
OpenAI co-founder released Auto Research — a six hundred thirty

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
line Python script, open source under M-I-T license, that demonstrates

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
autonomous A-I self-improvement on a single G-P-U. The concept is

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
deceptively simple. Give an A-I agent a small but real

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
language model training setup. Let it experiment autonomously — modifying

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
the training code, running a five-minute training run, checking whether

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
the loss improved, keeping or discarding the change, and repeating.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
The human writes the prompt. The A-I iterates on the

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
code. After two days, Auto Research had processed approximately seven

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
hundred autonomous experiments, finding roughly twenty additive improvements that transferred

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
perfectly to larger models. The result: an eleven percent reduction

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
in the "Time to G-P-T two" benchmark, from two point

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
zero two hours to one point eight zero hours. Not

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
a theoretical improvement on a toy problem — an eleven

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
percent efficiency gain on training a real language model, discovered

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
entirely by machine. The repo went viral: eight point six

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
million views on X, over forty-two thousand GitHub stars within

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
days. More importantly, the pattern proved generalizable. Shopify C-E-O Tobi

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Lütke applied the Auto Research loop to optimize rendering speed,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
producing ninety-three automated commits that achieved fifty-three percent faster rendering

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
and sixty-one percent reduction in memory allocations. The message was

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
clear: this isn't just for A-I research. The self-improvement loop

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
works on anything you can score. Now let's turn to

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
the governance gap — because this is where the story

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
turns from impressive to unsettling. Dean Ball's policy analysis is

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
the sharpest available on this point. He identifies the current

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
state of affairs bluntly: there are no safety or security

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
standards for frontier models, no cybersecurity rules for frontier labs

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
or data centers, no requirements for explainability or testing for

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
A-I systems engineered by other A-I systems, and no specific

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
legal constraints on what frontier labs can do with the

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
results of recursive self-improvement. The academic community hasn't covered itself

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
in glory either. The I-C-L-R twenty twenty-six Workshop on A-I

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
with Recursive Self-Improvement — possibly the world's first academic workshop

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
dedicated entirely to R-S-I, scheduled for April twenty-sixth in Rio

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
de Janeiro — initially gave safety concerns minimal emphasis. When

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
journalists pressed the organizers, safety was subsequently added as "encouraged,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
optional." Optional. David Scott Krueger, a University of Cambridge A-I

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
safety researcher, was less diplomatic: "It's completely wild and crazy

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
that this is happening, it's unconscionable." The paradox is stark.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
The people closest to the technology freely acknowledge the risks.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
Kaplan calls it "the ultimate risk." Hassabis wonders publicly whether

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
the loop can close safely. Altman hedges his timeline announcements

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
with notes about "extraordinary potential impacts." But the organizational incentive

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
is to keep building. Every lab operates under the same

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
competitive logic: if we don't build it first, someone else

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
will. The claim to responsibility, however, rests on safety infrastructure

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
that does not yet exist. Before getting swept up in

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
the intelligence explosion narrative, it's worth considering the skeptical case

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
— because there is one, and it's not trivial. LeCun's

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
bet against the R-S-I paradigm is the most prominent version.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
His argument, simplified: current language models are prediction machines, not

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
reasoning engines. They can optimize within a paradigm — write

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
better code, tune hyperparameters, find efficiency gains — but they

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
cannot make the kind of paradigm-shifting conceptual leaps that transform

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
fields. Auto Research found a nice eleven percent improvement, but

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
it found it by iterating within an existing architecture, not

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
by inventing a new one. Ball frames this as his

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
"bearish scenario": A-I automation accelerates progress within existing paradigms, but

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
the acceleration looks like driving a car faster on a

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
highway rather than learning to fly. The economic impact is

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
enormous — automated research dramatically reduces costs and increases output

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
— but the intelligence explosion never actually detonates. There's also

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
a practical scaffolding problem. Current A-I agents excel at short-horizon

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
tasks — write a function, optimize a parameter, run an

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
experiment. But A-I research is not a sequence of short-horizon

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.000
tasks. It requires maintaining coherent research programs over weeks and

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
months, integrating results across subfields, recognizing when a dead end

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
is actually a new direction. OpenAI's September twenty twenty-six target

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
for an A-I "intern" is telling: even the most optimistic

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.000
lab distinguishes between grunt work and genuine research capability. This

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
skepticism deserves serious weight. But it faces a challenge: the

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:28.000
labs pursuing R-S-I have consistently delivered on aggressive timelines that

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
skeptics said were impossible. Two years ago, "A-I writes ninety

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
percent of its own code" would have been dismissed as

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
Silicon Valley fantasy. It's an Anthropic press statement now. So

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
what's actually at stake? The honest assessment, sitting with everything

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
the research turned up, is this: recursive self-improvement is the

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
most consequential development in A-I right now, and it is

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
happening with remarkably little public scrutiny. Ball predicts that during

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
twenty twenty-six, the effective "workforces" of each frontier lab will

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
grow from single-digit thousands to tens of thousands, and then

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
hundreds of thousands — most of them artificial. These workforces

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
will grow smarter each month, not only because A-I was

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
already improving rapidly but because their only objective will be

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.000
to make themselves smarter. Whether this produces a genuine intelligence

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
explosion or merely a very fast improvement within existing paradigms

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
is the most important empirical question in technology today. The

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
answer might not be knowable in advance. And that is

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
precisely the problem. Several concrete markers in the coming months

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
will signal how fast the loop is tightening. The I-C-L-R

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
R-S-I Workshop on April twenty-sixth — the first major academic

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
gathering focused entirely on recursive self-improvement. Whether safety gets real

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
attention or remains "optional" will reveal where the research community's

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
priorities actually lie. OpenAI's September twenty twenty-six target for an

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
automated A-I research intern. Anthropic's twenty twenty-seven horizon for fully

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
automated A-I research. And whether any jurisdiction moves beyond self-reporting

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
toward independent verification infrastructure. The absence of governance action is

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
itself a signal. I. J. Good's nineteen sixty-five thought experiment

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
ended with a sentence that has aged better than any

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
line in the history of technology forecasting: "Thus the first

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
ultraintelligent machine is the last invention that man need ever

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
make, provided that the machine is docile enough to tell

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
us how to keep it under control." Sixty-one years later,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
the first half of that sentence is closer to reality

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
than most people understand. The second half — the part

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.000
about control — remains entirely unresolved. That's the recursive self-improvement

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.000
deep dive. Full post and sources at jacob brooke ninety-five

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.000
dot github dot i-o slash jacobs research journal. Thanks for

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:52.400
listening.
